		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I collect games and I want the single cartridges to be in my shelf just like the real deal would be. </div>
<br />I'm sorry, but I think it doesn't really make sense. If you make a repro, it will just be like a pirated cart (altough it's for personal use). By definition, collectors would typically wants only real carts. If it was a game you really like and hope to play it on the real hardware in your language, it would make much sense.
<br />
<br />Anyway, we can't help you much without you to tell use the title of the game you want to reproduce. It may be very easy or downright impossible depending on the mapper the game uses. If you really don't want to give the title to us for some reson (why would you anyway ?) you must at least copy the iNES header so we know the size and mapper of the ROM.
<br />
<br />To copy permanently, in the best case you need :
<br />- A donor cart
<br />- Some way to crack the cart open without damaging the plastic case
<br />- One or two EPROMs
<br />- A soldering iron, solder, and a disoldering pump
<br />
<br />In the worse scenarios, depending on the mapper you will also need some of these:
<br />- Wires and a cutter to cut traces (very likely).
<br />- A very rare famicom donor cart which is annoying to find and has a ridiculous price thanks to collectors
<br />- Other electronics parts to add to the cricuit
<br />- Modify a Famicom to NES adapter and modify your NES to get extra audio
<br />
<br />Oh, and if you don't understand english well, but understand french better, I can help you, else I can't.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
